fr.sii.ogham.core.util

Class PropertyListOrValue<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • fr.sii.ogham.core.util.PropertyListOrValue<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - The type of the value
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    EncoderBuilder.StandardEncodingHelper

    public class PropertyListOrValue<T>
extends Object
    Utility class for builders that allow to either use a property or use direct value.

    The helper registers one or several property keys. For example: 

     .register("${custom.property.high-priority}", "${custom.property.low-priority}");
    The properties are not immediately evaluated. The evaluation will be done when the Builder.build() method is called. If you provide several property keys, evaluation will be done on the first key and if the property exists (see EnvironmentBuilder), its value is used. If the first property doesn't exist in properties, then it tries with the second one and so on. You can specify a direct value as a string. For example: 
     .register("${custom.property.high-priority}", "true");
    If the property "custom.property.high-priority" doesn't exist then "true" is always used (any other property or value registered later is not used).

    You can also register a direct value using the right type (register(Object)). If not specified, the direct value is appended. For example, 

      
 .register("${custom.property.high-priority}")
 .register(true)
    If "custom.property.high-priority" property doesn't exist, then .register(true) is used. If "custom.property.high-priority" property exists, then the value of "custom.property.high-priority" is used. 
      
 .register(true)
 .register("${custom.property.high-priority}")
    The value of .register(true) is always used.

    It is also possible to force override.

 .register(true)

      • register

        public void register(T value,
                     boolean override)

        Registers a direct value using the right type (register(Object)). If override is true, the direct value is added at the beginning so it has highest priority.

        If override parameter is false, then this method behaves exactly the same as register(Object).

        Parameters:
        value - the value to register
        override - the value is registered with highest priority

      • register

        public void register(String... property)
        Registers one or several property keys. For example: 
         .register("${custom.property.high-priority}", "${custom.property.low-priority}");
        The properties are not immediately evaluated. The evaluation will be done when the Builder.build() method is called. If you provide several property keys, evaluation will be done on the first key and if the property exists (see EnvironmentBuilder), its value is used. If the first property doesn't exist in properties, then it tries with the second one and so on. You can specify a direct value as a string. For example: 
         .register("${custom.property.high-priority}", "true", "${custom.property.low-priority}");
        If the property "custom.property.high-priority" doesn't exist then "true" is always used (any other property or value registered later is not used).
        Parameters:
        property - one value, or one or several property keys
